Text: On "Old Twitter" (before and around September 2010), Twitter left that development up to the aftermarket and focused on making their platform rock solid. Even features like in-line image and video posting was largely done through 3rd parties. And it worked. It was clunky, but it worked.

Reply_1_Text: That aftermarket led to the creation of apps and programs like TweetDeck, Hootsuite, and a bunch of other marketing tools. And they competed against each other regularly. And they improved regularly because of that competitive market. Some of that functionality still wasn't present at Elon's buying.

Reply_2_Text: no, you only lose your user name (you become "unverified"); you just choose another one and you are back in the game -- all connections preserved
Reply_3_Text: The domain is an alias for your account, so it can be changed to a different username without affecting content or followers.
Reply_4_Text: domain names are cheap. It's a simple, elegant, and low-cost way to handle personal verification.
Reply_5_Text: FWIW
Reply_6_Text: No, you won't lose your identity, but you will have to rename it. The underlying identifier (the "real" you) is a DID (distributed identifier); the @domain.whatever part is a handle (an "also known as") - and you'd change that.
Reply_7_Text:
Think of Bluesky validation as... a Self Addressed Stamped Envelope.

You tell Bluesky "I live at nytimes" (or whatever), and they send a letter to nytimes.  If nytimes responds by sending back the (equivalent of) the SASE, you're verified. If not, not.

nytimes doesn't own the acct after that.
Reply_8_Text:
No. You own your info that's the point.

The handle isn't the account and can be changed.

Previous handles will be visible in the data.

Think of it as an automatic resume.
